            <h1>Safety Hazards</h1>
            <p>Certain potential losses must be accounted for when working with patients and potential hazards in-lab. Losses are not attributed to human error and may include but are not limited to loss impacting stakeholders, environmental damage, injury to persons, etc. Identifying these scenarios ultimately helps to prevent them from occurring and aid the generation of appropriate emergency responses. This approach to hazard analysis is referred to as a Systems Theoretic Process Analysis (STPA). The STPA varies from other methods as it treats accidents as losses of control rather than outright failure. Thoroughly examining hazards related to all forms of failure allows for a more structured approach to risk mitigation. The first step to performing a STPA is to define a system boundary (to avoid an endless breakdown of a system into small insignificant parts), as well as the losses of the specific system and their associated hazards. In regards to the proposed biosensor, the following nine potential losses were considered:</p> <br>

