            <p>The second step of an STPA is to create a control structure, which clearly denotes a hierarchy of control within staff and describes the impact different pieces of the system have on one another. This is done with the goal of identifying potentially hazardous system interactions and ensures there is no confusion as to who overrides whom in an emergency scenario. Next, the third step is to identify any Unsafe Control Actions (UCAs). UCAs are actions derived from the control structure that could ultimately lead to a hazard. Lastly, step five consists of the identification of causal scenarios, which are actions that could lead to the previously identified unsafe control actions. A risk mitigation plan can then be created with the goal of preventing hazards/losses through avoidance of UCAs as well as causal scenarios. Through examining the various potential hazards associated with both the production and use of our proposed biosensor, the team can be proactive in regards to risk mitigation. Implementing a robust and comprehensive emergency protocol will help reduce confusion and lessen the damages and/or losses that could occur in certain situations. This would also result in more informed, prepared, and trained staff. </p>
